<div class="dablink">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Genie_(disambiguation)" title="Genie (disambiguation)">Genie (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Islam" title="Islam">Islam</a> and <a href="/wiki/Arabian_mythology" title="Arabian mythology">pre-Islamic Arabian folklore</a>, a <b>genie</b> (also <b>jinn</b>, <b>djinn</b>, from <a href="/wiki/Arabic_language" title="Arabic language">Arabic</a> <b>جني</b> <i>jinnī</i>) is a <a href="/wiki/Supernatural" title="Supernatural">supernatural</a> creature which possesses free will. Genies are mentioned in the <a href="/wiki/Qur%27an" title="Qur'an">Qur'an</a>, wherein a whole <a href="/wiki/Sura" title="Sura">Sura</a> is named after them (<a href="/wiki/Al-Jinn" title="Al-Jinn">Al-Jinn</a>). They can be either good or evil. In some cases, evil genies are said to lead humans astray. In <a href="/wiki/Islam" title="Islam">Islam</a>, <a href="/wiki/Satan" title="Satan">Satan</a>, known in Arabic as <a href="/wiki/Iblis" title="Iblis">Iblis</a>, is the iconic genie that refused to bow down to <a href="/wiki/Adam" title="Adam">Adam</a> when ordered to by <a href="/wiki/Allah" title="Allah">Allah</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
